# Post-Phase Stability Rule (Pack K + Pack L Locked)

## Purpose
This rule locks the behaviors verified in the Post-Phase stability passes after Phase 0–8 completion.

These tests confirmed that the Parallel rotation engine is stable across:
- team-size / performance stress
- supported rotation-week boundaries
- fixed-base-time anchor behavior
- fallback / strict mode explainability
- hard-boundary pre-generation guards

Any future change must preserve these verified behaviors.

---

## Locked Verified Behaviors

### 1) Team Size / Performance Stability
Verified:
- ~9-person real multi-timezone team generates successfully
- ~18-person constrained team fails gracefully when no shared hard-valid candidate exists
- runtime remains fast (~2 seconds observed)
- UI remains responsive
- solver does not silently fail

Must preserve:
- no crash under moderate team size
- no UI freeze during generation
- no hidden solver failure
- honest no-candidate state when hard constraints eliminate all candidates

Do not:
- introduce expensive loops or repeated recomputation in schedule generation
- add noisy logging that materially impacts generation performance
- bypass hard-boundary candidate pruning

---

### 2) No-Candidate Hard-Boundary Guard
Verified:
- when no shared time fits everyone's hard limits, system stops before solver-mode generation
- UI correctly shows "No shared time fits everyone's limits"
- system may offer relaxation path, but does not fabricate a plan

Must preserve:
- hard boundaries remain absolute
- pre-solver guard triggers before any fake STRICT / RELAXED / FALLBACK result
- no schedule is generated if zero hard-valid candidates exist

Do not:
- silently downgrade hard boundaries into soft rules
- produce a schedule when hard-valid candidate count is zero
- invent modeUsed / forcedReason output for a pre-solver no-candidate case

---

### 3) Supported Rotation Week Boundaries
Verified supported UI boundary:
- minimum supported rotationWeeks = 4
- maximum supported rotationWeeks = 12

Verified generation behavior:
- 4-week schedules generate correctly
- 12-week schedules generate correctly
- no truncation
- no overflow
- no missing or extra weeks
- no week-index corruption

Must preserve:
- exact schedule length equals requested rotationWeeks
- 4 and 12 remain stable boundary values
- long-cycle generation remains deterministic and fast

Do not:
- reintroduce implicit 8-week assumptions
- hardcode schedule length independent of rotationWeeks
- produce Week 13 for a 12-week cycle
- truncate 12-week output to 8 weeks

---

### 4) Fixed Base Time / Anchor Mode
Verified:
- fixed base time is not allowed to violate hard boundaries
- invalid fixed time is blocked pre-generation with UI warning
- valid fixed base time generates stable anchor-mode schedules
- in anchor mode, all generated weeks use the same reference time
- anchor mode remained stable at both 4 weeks and 12 weeks

Observed verified behavior:
- chosen UI base time may anchor to the nearest viable schedule time
- resulting anchor time remains stable across all weeks once generated

Must preserve:
- fixed base time cannot bypass hard constraints
- anchor mode must keep a stable repeated reference time across all weeks
- no week-to-week time drift in anchor mode
- UI messaging must remain consistent with anchor behavior

Do not:
- treat fixed base time as permission to violate hard_no_ranges
- allow anchor schedules to drift across weeks
- claim "time rotates" when anchor mode is active
- silently fall back into rotating-time mode when fixed-base mode is enabled

---

### 5) Solver Mode Honesty
Verified:
- STRICT appears only when fairness-valid plan exists
- FALLBACK appears when beam search exhausts fairness-valid search
- forcedReason = BEAM_EXHAUSTED appears when appropriate
- explain text matches actual solver behavior
- no fake fairness claims are shown

Must preserve:
- modeUsed must reflect actual solver path
- shareablePlanExists must reflect actual fairness-valid result
- forcedReason must only appear when actually triggered
- explain text must match solver reality

Do not:
- relabel fallback schedules as fair
- claim balanced rotation when constraints prevent it
- suppress forcedReason when beam exhaustion actually occurred
- output STRICT if fairness-valid constraints were not met

---

### 6) Deterministic Repetition Is Allowed
Verified:
- for constrained teams, the solver may repeatedly select the same viable local optimum
- repeated weekly times are valid if candidate space is narrow
- repeated patterns are not a bug by themselves

Must preserve:
- deterministic outputs for identical inputs
- repeated schedule patterns are acceptable when constraints justify them

Do not:
- inject randomness to make schedules "look more rotated"
- treat repeated viable times as an automatic bug
- force artificial diversity that changes solver correctness

---

### 7) Burden / Explain Consistency
Verified:
- burden summaries matched actual visible inconvenience distribution
- anchor-mode schedules concentrate burden on fixed disadvantaged members
- rotating schedules may still concentrate burden on Asia / Europe when geography makes fairness bounded
- explanation text remained honest about impossibility of full rotation in some weeks

Must preserve:
- burden summaries must match generated schedule reality
- highlighted stretched members must match actual local-time discomfort
- explain text must remain grounded in actual constraints

Do not:
- compute burden summaries from a different logic path than rendered schedules
- highlight the wrong members
- claim equal distribution when burden metrics clearly show otherwise

---

## Change Control
For any future modification touching:
- rotationWeeks
- fixed base time / anchor mode
- candidate generation
- hard-boundary filtering
- solver mode reporting
- explain text
- burden summary
- generation performance

Cursor must:
1. propose the smallest possible change set
2. preserve all verified Post-Phase behaviors above
3. avoid refactors unless explicitly approved
4. state clearly whether the change affects:
   - pre-solver candidate guard
   - solver search behavior
   - anchor mode behavior
   - explain / burden rendering only

---

## Regression Expectations
After any relevant change, re-check at minimum:

### Performance
- moderate team still generates quickly
- constrained larger team still fails gracefully without crashing

### Rotation Week Boundary
- 4 weeks works
- 12 weeks works

### Anchor Mode
- invalid fixed time is blocked
- valid fixed time generates stable repeated reference time

### Mode Reporting
- STRICT still only appears for fairness-valid plans
- FALLBACK still appears when beam search exhausts

### Honesty
- no fake fairness text
- no fabricated schedule when no hard-valid candidate exists

---

## Non-Negotiable Rule
Do not change verified behavior merely to make schedules appear more fair, more diverse, or more visually pleasing.

Correctness, honesty, hard-boundary integrity, and deterministic stability take priority over cosmetic rotation variety.

# Pack M Behavior Rule — Real Asymmetric Teams

## Purpose

Pack M verified solver behavior for asymmetric global teams.

Parallel must prioritize **correctness and honesty**
over visually appearing fair.

---

## Locked Behaviors

1. Asymmetric teams may produce partially repeated meeting times.

2. The solver may insert occasional alternate weeks
to distribute burden when possible.

3. Some members (often Asia or Europe) may still carry higher burden
due to geography.

This is expected behavior.

---

## Do Not

- artificially force time diversity
- inject randomness to "look fairer"
- suppress real burden differences
- fabricate rotation when constraints prevent it

---

## Core Principle

Parallel distributes inconvenience **when possible**.

It must never pretend that fairness exists when geography makes it impossible.
